# Product Vision And Structure

- Build a React Native mobile app for distributed physical-world data collection.
- The product must serve two audiences: everyday contributors capturing objects and data buyers needing useful physical-world datasets.
- Contributor experience comes first: the capture loop must feel simple, rewarding, trustworthy, and lightweight enough for idle moments.
- Data buyer needs matter, but should not leak complexity into the contributor UI.
- Avoid premature decisions about final data format. Captures may remain raw media, annotated media, reconstructed assets, metadata-rich records, or another buyer-ready format.
- AI auto-categorization of captures (vision model classifying category/subject from photos + location metadata) is explicitly in scope. Other speculative AI/3D pipeline work still requires an explicit task or PRD change.
- Keep product language concrete: capture, submit, review, earn, request, package.
- Keep the core loop visible in all feature work: capture anything, submit, receive feedback, earn. Suggested tasks (opportunities) are optional boosters, never the entry point.

## Project Structure

- Prefer a clear feature-oriented structure over a layer-only structure.
- Keep app entry, routing, and navigation thin. Product logic belongs in feature modules.
- Organize contributor flows, buyer/admin flows, capture logic, rewards, review, and dataset packaging as distinct domains.
- Shared UI primitives, design tokens, hooks, utilities, API clients, storage adapters, and types should live in predictable shared locations.
- Platform-specific code should be isolated behind narrow interfaces or platform-specific files when behavior meaningfully differs by iOS and Android.
- Keep native code rare and deliberate. React Native documentation currently recommends Expo for new production apps; prefer that path unless a clear native requirement justifies otherwise.
- Do not let screens become orchestration dumping grounds. Extract state, domain logic, and reusable UI before a screen becomes hard to scan.
- Treat tests, mocks, and fixtures as first-class project structure, not afterthoughts.
